model_explanation: the prosodic focus in S1 is on ROB, meaning Sam gave bananas only to Rob and no one else. Therefore, it entails that Sam didn’t give bananas to Tom or anyone else.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on TOM, meaning Sam gave grapes only to Tom, and no other item to Tom. This means it entails that Sam didn’t give Tom oranges.

the prosodic focus in S1 is on SUE, meaning Sam gave oranges to Sue and didn’t give oranges to anyone else. It does not rule out giving Sue other things. But S2 states Sam also gave Sue apples, which contradicts the typical implication of exclusivity under the assumption that “only” might extend to the item in typical use.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on SUE, meaning Sam gave bananas only to Sue and not to anyone else. Therefore, it entails that Sam didn’t give Rob bananas.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on ORANGES, meaning that Sam gave Tom only oranges and nothing else. Therefore, it entails that Sam didn’t give Tom bananas.

the prosodic focus in S1 is on SUE, meaning Sam gave apples only to Sue and did not give apples to anyone else. This doesn’t entail anything about what else Sue did or didn’t receive, making S2 independent.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on GRAPES, meaning Sam gave Sue only grapes and nothing else. Therefore, it entails that Sam didn’t give Sue apples.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on ORANGES, meaning Sam gave Ellen only oranges and nothing else. S2 says Sam also gave Ellen bananas, which directly contradicts that.
the prosodic focus in S1 is on GRAPES, meaning Sam gave Mary only grapes and nothing else. Therefore, it entails that Sam didn’t give Mary apples.

the prosodic focus in S1 is on BILL, meaning Sam gave oranges only to Bill and not to anyone else. S2 states that Sam also gave Mary oranges, which is independent from the claim about Bill and doesn’t follow from or contradict S1 directly. It’s about another person entirely, making it independent.
